875
00:42:56,837 --> 00:42:56,967
Scott: Yup.

876
00:42:57,090 --> 00:42:58,389
Scott: Even with Valve with their VAC.

877
00:42:58,770 --> 00:43:01,569
Rym: Or people don't cheat and get accused of cheating, like me.

878
00:43:02,138 --> 00:43:02,244
Scott: Yeah.

879
00:43:02,430 --> 00:43:04,929
Rym: I got kicked and banned from a server not that long ago.

880
00:43:05,471 --> 00:43:10,600
Scott: And if people online gambled like crazy, it's like someone would hit jackpots.

881
00:43:10,780 --> 00:43:16,650
Scott: pretty, you know, it's like, yeah, the percentage of people hitting jackpots would be about the same, but the absolute number would go way up.

882
00:43:16,950 --> 00:43:26,410
Rym: It kind of delves into non-Monday territory, but I suspect that if you did a huge study of people who gamble online, there's two distinct classes.

883
00:43:26,831 --> 00:43:37,770
Rym: There are the people who gamble because it's fun to gamble with friends, maybe for money, like they're doing it for money or whatever, but they're doing it not to make a living, they're doing it because it's fun.

884
00:43:38,551 --> 00:43:45,070
Rym: And then there's the much bigger group of people who are doing it to make money or because they think it's easy money.

885
00:43:45,931 --> 00:43:53,226
Scott: And the latter- I know a lot of people, especially college age dudes, basically try to do like online poker as their job.

886
00:43:53,246 --> 00:43:54,930
Scott: They thought they were so good at it or whatever.

887
00:43:55,190 --> 00:44:00,160
Rym: Yup, because those sites, I mean, part of the reason they do it is that you start to trust the sites because they do pay out.

888
00:44:01,422 --> 00:44:03,967
Rym: They do pay out, but they don't pay out forever.

889
00:44:03,987 --> 00:44:05,830
Rym: They don't pay out all the time.

890
00:44:07,190 --> 00:44:11,758
Rym: In fact, because they're not regulated, they could pay out a lot early on and then not pay out anymore.

891
00:44:12,118 --> 00:44:19,010
Rym: And as long as it takes you longer to figure out it's not paying out anymore, then the time it took you to build up the money you'd gotten, it's a net profit for them.

892
00:44:19,378 --> 00:44:19,569
Rym: Yup.

893
00:44:19,830 --> 00:44:22,894
Rym: And it caused them almost nothing to do because the security stuff's pretty easy.

894
00:44:22,914 --> 00:44:25,458
Rym: There's another factor with the circle of trust.

895
00:44:25,898 --> 00:44:30,144
Rym: If I want to gamble online, I have to trust the fuck out of that casino.

896
00:44:30,505 --> 00:44:32,868
Rym: Casino doesn't have to trust me at all.

897
00:44:33,208 --> 00:44:34,570
Rym: It's got my money, it could just disappear.

898
00:44:35,850 --> 00:44:37,515
Rym: So it's a one-sided arrangement.

899
00:44:37,656 --> 00:44:42,330
Rym: Only one party is hurt by a lack of trust or a failure to uphold trust.

900
00:44:42,811 --> 00:44:51,650
Rym: As soon as you're communicating with someone where the other party will be harmed if you break the trust, but you are not harmed if they break the trust, it's very similar to the game theory.

901
00:44:51,650 --> 00:44:53,410
Scott: You're basically relying on them to be nice.

902
00:44:54,550 --> 00:44:55,809
Scott: Please be nice and don't fuck me.

903
00:44:56,270 --> 00:44:59,910
Rym: I mean, if I have nukes and you don't, you just have to trust me and not use nukes.

904
00:44:59,990 --> 00:45:01,151
