923
00:46:15,170 --> 00:46:16,717
Rym: Well, that's why there's no house.

924
00:46:17,158 --> 00:46:18,986
Rym: The house takes a rake or a cut.

925
00:46:19,067 --> 00:46:20,545
Scott: It's just like- Oh, like poker?

926
00:46:20,565 --> 00:46:20,749
Scott: Yeah.

927
00:46:20,870 --> 00:46:21,392
Rym: Like poker.

928
00:46:21,432 --> 00:46:26,750
Rym: That's the interesting kind of gambling where you set up a system where people are gambling with other people.

929
00:46:27,151 --> 00:46:28,235
Rym: You just take a cut.

930
00:46:28,737 --> 00:46:31,890
Rym: Now, you're just, you're the broker of trust.

931
00:46:32,690 --> 00:46:36,910
Rym: Security-wise, it's such an elegant analogy for how to do secure networks.

932
00:46:37,311 --> 00:46:46,890
Rym: If you do a game like Texas Hold'em and you want to be the casino, you now have a vested interest in making sure that all the people playing trust you.

933
00:46:47,131 --> 00:46:51,410
Rym: Because if you're, if people stop trusting you, your business disappears.

934
00:46:51,930 --> 00:46:54,869
Rym: Your cut is only from the fact that people trust you.

935
00:46:55,331 --> 00:47:02,510
Rym: So now everyone has an incentive to validate your trust or their trust of you and you have an incentive to maintain that trust.

936
00:47:02,772 --> 00:47:05,770
Rym: And then everybody gets what they want, except the people who lose at poker.

937
00:47:07,414 --> 00:47:08,689
Scott: But I guess in a way they get what they want.

938
00:47:08,770 --> 00:47:16,390
Scott: It's like, yeah, we could set up a thing where it's like, you know, it's Counter-Strike and you just bet on actual Counter-Strike games and we don't take any of the money.

939
00:47:16,470 --> 00:47:22,630
